[[File:Lea Roback.jpg|thumbnail|200px|Léa Roback photo in the collection of the [[Jewish Public Library (Montreal)|Jewish Public Library]]]] '''Léa Roback''' (3 November 1903<ref name=jewishpubliclibrary.org>{{cite web|title=The Adventures of Lea Roback|url=http://www.jewishpubliclibrary.org/blog/?page_id=1353|publisher=Jewish Public Library|accessdate=10 May 2014}}</ref> &ndash; 28 August 2000) was a Canadian [[trade union]] organizer, social activist, pacifist, and feminist. She campaigned against exclusion, violence, racism and injustice.<ref name=ordre-national.gouv.qc.ca /> A [[polyglot]] and a [[Suffragette|suffragist]], she was a pioneer of feminism in [[Quebec]]. A [[Syndicalism|Syndicalist]],<ref name=Ferretti1990>{{cite journal|last=Ferretti|first=Lucia|title=''Madeleine Parent, Léa Roback, Entretiens avec Nicole Lacelle'' by Nicole Lacelle|journal=Labour/Le Travail|volume=25|year= 1990|page=247&ndash;249|url=http://journals.hil.unb.ca/index.php/LLT/article/viewFile/4769/5642|accessdate=10 May 2014|language=French}}</ref> [[Communist]] and a [[Marxist]], she opened the first Marxist book store in [[Montreal]].
==Early years== Born in Montreal on Guilbault Street in 1903, the second of nine children,<ref name=collectionscanada.gc.ca2010>{{cite web|title=Léa Roback|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/women/030001-1114-e.html|publisher=[[Library and Archives Canada]]|accessdate=10 May 2014|date=16 September 2010}}</ref> she was the daughter of [[Polish Jews|Polish Jewish]] immigrants. Her father was a tailor who, along with his wife, Fanny, ran a general store. They were the only Jews in [[Beauport, Quebec City|Beauport]], the town where Roback grew up.<ref name=fondationlearoback.org>{{cite web|title=Lea’s biography|url=http://www.fondationlearoback.org/bioen.htm|publisher=Fondation Lea Roback|accessdate=10 May 2014}}</ref> She spoke [[Yiddish]] at home, French with Beauport locals, and English at school. Her family valued reading and the arts. In her youth, she was influenced by her maternal grandmother, an independent woman.
With her family, Roback returned to Montreal in 1915. While working at British American Dyeworks, she became aware of the differences between the various sectors of Montreal society. Her next job was as a cashier at [[Her Majesty's Theatre, Montreal|Her Majesty's Theatre]]. Interested in literature, she saved money to enroll at the [[University of Grenoble]] in 1926,<ref name=fondationlearoback.org /> earning a Bachelor of Arts degree.<ref name="Forster2004">{{cite book|last=Forster|first=Merna|title=100 Canadian Heroines: Famous and Forgotten Faces|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D9NAciHwjUAC&pg=PA214|year=2004|publisher=Dundurn|isbn=978-1-55002-514-9|page=214}}</ref> On her return from Grenoble, she joined her sister in [[New York City]]. In 1929, she went to [[Berlin]] to visit her brother Henri, a medical student. She learned the German language, took university courses, and taught English.<ref name=Forster2004 /> She also visited England and Italy,<ref name=ordre-national.gouv.qc.ca>{{cite web|title=Léa Roback (1903–2000) Chevalière (2000)|url=http://www.ordre-national.gouv.qc.ca/membres/membre.asp?id=1239|publisher=Gouvernement du Québec|accessdate=10 May 2014|language=French}}</ref> developing a strong commitment to [[Communism]].<ref name="LindleyStebner2008">{{cite book|last1=Lindley|first1=Susan Hill|last2=Stebner|first2=Eleanor J.|title=The Westminster Handbook to Women in American Religious History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R4hLAtDBHskC&pg=PA183|year=2008|publisher=[[Westminster John Knox Press]]|isbn=978-0-664-22454-7|page=183}}</ref>
==Career== In 1929, Roback became a member of the [[Communist Party of Canada]]. She felt seduced by [[History of the socialist movement in Canada|the socialists]], but she believed they did not put their words into action, hence she shifted her support to [[Marxism]]-[[Leninism]]. In her 1988 interview with Nicole Lacelle, Roback said that it was during this period that she gained genuine political consciousness. In the fall of 1932, when the war in Europe escalated, Roback, a Jew and a foreigner, was forced to leave return to Montreal. In 1934, she spent a few months in the [[Soviet Union]] with a lover.{{efn|Roback married in Europe at some point, but the marriage was annulled.<ref name=Forster2004 />}} Returning for good to Montreal, she participated in the organization of the unemployed, which was led by [[Norman Bethune]]. She also worked at the Young Women's Hebrew Association. In 1935, she established the first Marxist bookshop in Montreal,<ref name=Forster2004 /> Modern Book Shop.<ref name=fondationlearoback.org /> {{Quote box | quote ="There is nothing that I like better than to be standing on a street corner, passing out leaflets, because it is how you come to understand what people are about." (L. Roback)<ref name=collectionscanada.gc.ca2010 /><ref name=Forster2004 /> | width =25% | align =right }} With [[Thérèse Casgrain]], Roback fought for woman's suffrage in Quebec in 1936.<ref name=collectionscanada.gc.ca2010 /> In the same year, she worked with [[Rose Pesotta]], a veteran union organizer from New York, to establish the [[International Ladies' Garment Workers' Union]] (ILGWU) in Montreal, leading a strike of 5,000 women in 1937. Roback unionized [[RCA#Phonograph|RCA Victor]] in 1941, where she remained until 1951. She won the first union contract for women in 1943 but did not want to become a union representative or climb up union power structure. In the same year, Roback became a political organizer for [[Fred Rose (politician)|Fred Rose]].<ref name=fondationlearoback.org /> She left the Communist party in 1958.<ref name=Rioux2013>{{cite web|last=Rioux|first=Michel|title=Léa Roback|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/lea-roback/|work=The Canadian Encyclopedia|accessdate=10 May 2014|date=16 December 2013}}</ref>
In 1960, she became a member and played an active role in the organization "Voice of Women" (''La Voix des Femmes'' in Montreal)<ref name=fondationlearoback.org /> alongside [[Madeleine Parent]], [[Thérèse Casgrain]], and [[Simonne Monet-Chartrand]]. She denounced the [[Vietnam War]] and [[apartheid in South Africa]], campaigned against the proliferation of nuclear weapons, and was a proponent of free access to a quality education. A feminist, she fought to obtain the right to vote for the right to abortion and access to contraception. Roback also fought for the residents of [[Saint-Henri, Montreal|Saint-Henri]] to receive decent housing. At the age of 83 and in the pouring rain, she participated in the women's march for pay equity. In 1985, she became an honorary member of the Canadian Institute for Research on Women.<ref name=collectionscanada.gc.ca2010 /> She died in [[Côte-des-Neiges]] in 2000, becoming a Knight of the National Order of Quebec in the same year.
==Legacy== Her memory is perpetuated by the work of the Lea Roback Foundation, created in 1993,<ref name=collectionscanada.gc.ca2010 /> which provides scholarships to socially-committed women.<ref name=Rioux2013 /> "Le centre Léa-Roback", a research center in Montreal for social inequalities, is also named in her honour, as is the Maison Parent-Roback in [[Old Montreal]]. Sophie Bissonnette made a documentary on Roback's life in 1991.<ref name=fondationlearoback.org /> Two streets were named in her honour in the 2000s: Rue Léa-Roback in the Saint-Henri district of Montreal, and a street of the same name in Beauport, where she spent time in her youth.
The Léa Roback Foundation (Fondation Léa Roback) awards scholarships to women residing in Québec who are socially committed and economically disadvantaged.<ref>[http://www.fondationlearoback.org/home.htm Foundation]</ref>
