{{Infobox person |name= Sarah Jane Cooper |birth_name= Sarah Jane Gill |image= |image_size= |caption= |nationality=British |birth_date= 1848 |birth_place= [[Beoley]], [[Worcestershire]], [[England]] |death_date= 1932 |death_place= |occupation= [[Grocer]] and marmalade maker |spouse= [[Frank Cooper's#History|Frank Cooper]] |parents= |children= }}
[[File:Frank Cooper's.jpg|thumb|Oxford Marlamade, originally made by Sarah Cooper.]]
'''Sarah Jane Cooper''' (1848–1932) was an English [[marmalade]] maker and wife of [[Frank Cooper's#History|Frank Cooper]] (1844–1927).
Sarah Cooper was born Sarah Jane Gill in [[Beoley]], [[Worcestershire]] in 1848.<ref name=Plaque>{{cite web |url=http://www.oxfordshireblueplaques.org.uk/plaques/cooper.html|title=Sarah-Jane Cooper (1848–1932) |publisher=[[Oxfordshire Blue Plaques Board]] |date=15 September 2010 |accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref> In 1872 she got married in [[Clifton, Bristol]] to Frank Cooper of [[Oxford]] and they made their home at 31 [[Kingston Road, Oxford]].<ref name=Plaque/>
In 1867 Frank had inherited the family [[grocer]]y shop at 84 [[High Street, Oxford]].<ref name=Headington83>{{cite web |last=Jenkins |first=Stephanie |url=http://www.oxfordhistory.org.uk/high/tour/south/084.html |title=The High, Oxford: No 84 |work=Oxford History |publisher=Headington, Oxford |accessdate=18 March 2009}}</ref> In 1874 Frank expanded the business into 83 High Street next door, and the Coopers gave up their house in Kingston Road to live over the shop. Sarah, then aged 24, made {{convert|76|lb|kg}} of marmalade to her own recipe.<ref name=Headington83/> The marmalade became a regular product of Frank Cooper's business, being made behind the shop until 1903 when he moved production to a new purpose-built factory at 27 [[Park End Street]].<ref name=Woolley91>Woolley, 2010, page 91</ref>
Frank Cooper's business was taken over in 1964 and production left Oxford in 1967.<ref name=Woolley94>Woolley, 2010, page 94</ref> However, its marmalades and jams remain in production as a brand of [[Premier Foods]], which continues to call its leading Frank Cooper's product "Oxford" Marmalade. Since 2001, 84 High Street has been marked by an [[Oxfordshire Blue Plaques Board#Blue plaques in the City of Oxford|Oxfordshire Blue Plaque]] commemorating Sarah Cooper's achievement.<ref name="Plaque"/>
